Today’s lecture focused on advanced JDBC techniques, mainly the use of PreparedStatement and batch processing. 
The mentor explained that PreparedStatement is used to execute parameterized SQL queries. Unlike a normal Statement, 
a PreparedStatement is precompiled by the database, which improves performance when the same query is executed 
multiple times. It also provides better security because parameters are passed separately, helping prevent SQL 
injection attacks.

The session demonstrated how PreparedStatement uses placeholders (?) in SQL queries. Values are then assigned to 
these placeholders using methods such as setInt() and setString(). Once the parameters are set, the query can be 
executed using methods like executeUpdate() or executeQuery(). This approach makes database operations faster and 
more efficient when handling multiple records.

The mentor also introduced batch processing in JDBC. Batch processing allows multiple SQL commands to be grouped 
together and executed in a single request to the database. This reduces the number of database connections and improves 
application performance. Using methods like addBatch() and executeBatch(), several queries can be stored and executed together.

The working flow starts by establishing a database connection and creating a PreparedStatement object. SQL queries 
are prepared with placeholders for parameters. Values are assigned and added to the batch using addBatch(). 
When executeBatch() is called, all queries in the batch are executed together. This process reduces communication 
overhead between the application and the database.

Understanding PreparedStatement and batch processing is important because they improve the efficiency, security, 
and performance of database operations in real-world applications.